    {
      "id": 4935,
      "name": "",
      "username": "Alex",
      "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.trainerday.com/alex/{size}/1331_2.png",
      "created_at": "2022-01-11T09:45:29.393Z",
      "cooked": "<p>So generally you can read this thread.<br>\n<a href=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/t/slope-mode-like-erg-mode-completed/\">https://forums.trainerday.com/t/slope-mode-like-erg-mode-completed/</a></p>\n<p>Here are the steps you need to do</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Take a ramp test.  You can do this manually in our app, just adjust the watts to try to hit the target it shows.</li>\n<li>Determine your natural RPM when not thinking about it after you are warmed up for 10 minutes or so.  It\u2019s likely different at different intensities but just for a baseline</li>\n<li>Create conversion chart from slope % to watts</li>\n<li>Copy a workout from our DB and add slope %.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>See below for more details.</p>\n<p>I would determine what is your natural cadence and then create an approximate watts watts conversion for different slopes.</p>\n<p>Below is an example<br>\nAt 60rpm<br>\n0% = 50w<br>\n1% = 80w<br>\n2% = 100w</p>\n<p>Then you can find any workout in our database and copy it and add your percentage based on the watts you see, but make sure your FTP is semi-accurate first.<br>\n<div class=\"lightbox-wrapper\"><a class=\"lightbox\" href=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/original/1X/714b186399a23ec4309f17691e5fe308924011a5.png\" data-download-href=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/714b186399a23ec4309f17691e5fe308924011a5\" title=\"image\"><img src=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/optimized/1X/714b186399a23ec4309f17691e5fe308924011a5_2_443x499.png\" alt=\"image\" data-base62-sha1=\"gaeQojjzoqtSXfPDiWuvTAD4Nwh\" width=\"443\" height=\"499\" srcset=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/optimized/1X/714b186399a23ec4309f17691e5fe308924011a5_2_443x499.png, https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/original/1X/714b186399a23ec4309f17691e5fe308924011a5.png 1.5x, https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/original/1X/714b186399a23ec4309f17691e5fe308924011a5.png 2x\" data-small-upload=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/optimized/1X/714b186399a23ec4309f17691e5fe308924011a5_2_10x10.png\"><div class=\"meta\"><svg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><use xlink:href=\"#far-image\"></use></svg><span class=\"filename\">image</span><span class=\"informations\">618\u00d7696 45.6 KB</span><svg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><use xlink:href=\"#discourse-expand\"></use></svg></div></a></div></p>\n<p>If you are decent in excel you could do this with formulas so the whole conversion process only takes a minute or so.  You can copy and paste from our workout editor to excel and back.</p>\n<p>That\u2019s it. <img src=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/images/emoji/twitter/slight_smile.png?v=9\" title=\":slight_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":slight_smile:\"> If your RPM is semi-consistent this should be accurate enough for training purposes.  Let me know if you have any more questions.</p>",
